The paper proposes a deep learning method for compressive sensing image reconstruction, which involves computer vision (CV) and information theory (IT) concepts. The use of a fully-convolutional network and residual learning techniques suggests a focus on machine learning (LG) and multimedia (MM) subfields. Additionally, the joint training of the measurement and reconstruction stages implies a potential application of neural networks (NE) in optimization problems.
